column3: Balda, R. P. (1969). Foliage use by birds of the oak-juniper woodland and ponderosa pine forest in southeastern Arizona. The Condor, 71(4), 399-412.
column26: Foliage density, species specific stratification data
column59: Note that birds described in this study are not complete bird community; in another paper (linked below) he cites 36 sp. in juniper site (other paper does not describe ponderosa site). Richness at each vert strata inferred from occurence figures for each species: if >3% of observations within a strata, species considered present at that strata. Species occurences within each strata were then summed to obtain estimate of richness for each strata. Bird observation methods are available in Balda 1970, which report surveys for juniper site but not ponderosa site; sampling effort for ponderosa site assumed approx. equal to his other sites: https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/1366011.pdf?refreqid=excelsior%3A2d15429156da6d756ae42ceb1dcf04f4

Species occurences within each strata were then summed to obtain estimate of richness for each strata. Bird observation methods are available in Balda 1970, which report surveys for juniper site but not ponderosa site; sampling effort for ponderosa site assumed approx. equal to his other sites: https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/1366011.pdf?refreqid=excelsior%3A2d15429156da6d756ae42ceb1dcf04f4

Balda, R. P. (1969). Foliage use by birds of the oak-juniper woodland and ponderosa pine forest in southeastern Arizona. The Condor, 71(4), 399-412.
column26: Foliage density, species specific stratification data
column27: No methods on bird sampling provided in this paper, but are available in one of his other papers from this time: https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/1366011.pdf?refreqid=excelsior%3A2d15429156da6d756ae42ceb1dcf04f4
column59: Note that birds described in this study are not complete bird community; in another paper (linked below) he cites 36 sp. in juniper site (other paper does not describe ponderosa site). Richness at each vert strata inferred from occurence figures for each species: if >3% of observations within a strata, species considered present at that strata. Species occurences within each strata were then summed to obtain estimate of richness for each strata. Bird observation methods are available in Balda 1970, which report surveys for juniper site but not ponderosa site; sampling effort for ponderosa site assumed approx. equal to his other sites: https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/1366011.pdf?refreqid=excelsior%3A2d15429156da6d756ae42ceb1dcf04f4

column27: No methods on bird sampling provided in this paper, but are available in one of his other papers from this time: https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/1366011.pdf?refreqid=excelsior%3A2d15429156da6d756ae42ceb1dcf04f4
column59: Note that birds described in this study are not complete bird community; in another paper (linked below) he cites 36 sp. in juniper site (other paper does not describe ponderosa site). Richness at each vert strata inferred from occurence figures for each species: if >3% of observations within a strata, species considered present at that strata. Species occurences within each strata were then summed to obtain estimate of richness for each strata. Bird observation methods are available in Balda 1970, which report surveys for juniper site but not ponderosa site; sampling effort for ponderosa site assumed approx. equal to his other sites: https://www.jstor.org/stable/pdf/1366011.pdf?refreqid=excelsior%3A2d15429156da6d756ae42ceb1dcf04f4
